File: Engine/source/T3D/fx/explosion.cpp
Beginning at line 607

``` c++
   U32 count;
   for(count = 0; count < EC_NUM_TIME_KEYS; count++)
      if(times[i] >= 1)
         break;
```

Should probably read

``` c++
   U32 count;
   for(count = 0; count < EC_NUM_TIME_KEYS; count++)
      if(times[count] >= 1)
         break;
```

This isn't exactly an issue, just a reminder for myself, and others, to look at all the shaders in T3D and eliminate if's where possible.

A small test where I tried eliminating all if's from my new terrain blending shader gave a 0.5 MSPF reduction. (155FPS -> 165FPS)

E.g:

``` cpp
if( lerpBlend <= 0 ) 
{ 
   invBlend = 1-detailBlend0;
   ma = max(bumpNormal.a + detailBlend0, currentAlpha + invBlend) - blendDepth0;
   b1 = max(bumpNormal.a + detailBlend0 - ma, 0);
   b2 = max(currentAlpha + invBlend - ma, 0);
   currentAlpha = max(currentAlpha,bumpNormal.a);
}
IN.detCoord0.xy += parallaxOffset( normalMap0, IN.detCoord0.xy, negViewTS, detailIdStrengthParallax0.z * detailBlend0 );
if ( detailBlend0 > 0.0f )
{
   detailColor *= detailIdStrengthParallax0.y * IN.detCoord0.w;
   if( lerpBlend <= 0 ) 
      OUT.col.rgb = ((baseColor + detailColor).rgb * b1 + OUT.col.rgb * b2) / (b1 + b2);
   else
      OUT.col = lerp( OUT.col, baseColor + detailColor, detailBlend0 );
}
if( lerpBlend <= 0 ) 
   currentAlpha = (bumpNormal.a * b1 + currentAlpha * b2) / (b1 + b2);
```

Became:

``` cpp
invBlend = 1-detailBlend0;
ma = max(bumpNormal.a + detailBlend0, currentAlpha + invBlend) - blendDepth0;
b1 = max(bumpNormal.a + detailBlend0 - ma, 0);
b2 = max(currentAlpha + invBlend - ma, 0);
currentAlpha = max(currentAlpha,bumpNormal.a);
IN.detCoord0.xy += parallaxOffset( normalMap0, IN.detCoord0.xy, negViewTS, detailIdStrengthParallax0.z * detailBlend0 );
detailColor *= detailIdStrengthParallax0.y * IN.detCoord0.w;
OUT.col.rgb = ((baseColor + detailColor).rgb * b1 + OUT.col.rgb * b2) / (b1 + b2);
currentAlpha = (bumpNormal.a * b1 + currentAlpha * b2) / (b1 + b2);
```

This is because the GPU branches out on if-statements, and because of current GPU architecture, branching means it runs each branch for each pixel and discards the branches not used by the different pixels.

Meaning that if you have 1 if-statement, your code is run twice for each pixel.. Once for each possible outcome of the if-statement. It's best to try to avoid if's where possible to avoid this branching, even if it means doing some extra computations in the main body.

In Torque3D, BasicLightManager is created in a module, i.e. 

```
MODULE_BEGIN( BasicLightManager )
   MODULE_SHUTDOWN_AFTER( Scene )
   MODULE_INIT
   {
      ManagedSingleton< BasicLightManager >::createSingleton();
   }
   MODULE_SHUTDOWN
   {
      ManagedSingleton< BasicLightManager >::deleteSingleton();
   }
MODULE_END;
```

Simple enough. However this creates a problem with the light fields for each light object which are created via `LightManager::initLightFields()` (called from ::initPersistFields). This function iterates through each light manager and adds their fields to the object. However when ::initPersistFields is called, the module system hasn't been initialzed yet thus no fields will be added for BasicLightManager.

AdvancedLightManager doesn't have this problem since it's initialized on startup outside of the module system. However this introduces another problem: depending on the order in which AdvancedLightManager is destroyed, crashes can occur due to either memory corruption or invalid objects.

There is also an additional problem with BasicLightManager if you try to "fix" the problem using the AdvancedLightManager approach. In the constructor, it registers several console variables however this only works when the console system has been initialized, not before.

In short, the initialization order might need a rethink.

`EventManagerListener` uses a `SimpleHashTable`, which is case-sensitive by default. This usually doesn't come up, I think, because of the string table. However I've managed to crash the engine by requesting an event with the wrong capitalisation. It all goes wrong here:

``` cpp
bool EventManager::subscribe(SimObject *callbackObj, const char* event, const char* callback /*= NULL */)
{
   // Make sure the event is valid.
   if( !isRegisteredEvent( event ) )
   {
      Con::warnf( "EventManager::subscribe - %s is not a registered event.", event );
      return false;
   }

   ...

   Vector<EventManagerListener::Subscriber>* subscribers = mListener.mSubscribers.retreive( event );

   AssertFatal( subscribers, "Invalid event subscriber list." );

   subscribers->push_back( subscriber );

   return true;
}
```

The problem is that `isRegisteredEvent` uses the `StringTable`, so it makes case-insensitive comparisons:

``` cpp
bool EventManager::isRegisteredEvent( const char* event )
{
   // Iterate over the event list.
   StringTableEntry eventName = StringTable->insert( event );
   for( Vector<StringTableEntry>::const_iterator iter = mEvents.begin(); iter != mEvents.end(); iter++ )
   {
      // Found.
      if( *iter == eventName )
         return true;
   }

   // Not found.
   return false;
}
```

whereas `retrieve` does not, unless `mCaseSensitive` is set to `false`. Working on a simple example that will reproduce it, but I've made a quick fix by adding this to the definition of `EventManagerListener`:

``` cpp
public:
   EventManagerListener(): mSubscribers(64, false) {}
```

In a release build on OSX, (xcode 5.1.1), when global intern'd string (such as the GFX Semantics) is released upon shutdown memory corruption can occur. Specifically it seems the associated StringData is corrupted leading to a crash. This may propagate to other systems creating odd behaviour in random locations.

Adding a check such as follows seems to "fix" the problem

```
String::~String()
{
   if (!_string->isInterned())
      _string->release();
}
```

I'm still not too sure why this problem is occurring in the first place since adding watchpoints on the relevant memory addresses seems to indicate nothing is amiss, although I find it a little odd that the engine is creating a whole bunch of objects with allocated memory before the engine is initialized.

New terrain texture blending! As described [here](http://www.garagegames.com/community/blogs/view/22762/1#comment_form).

There is this thing called "blendDepth" that allows you to tweak how sharp the blending it is, to show you the effect of tweaking this depth I created the following album:
[http://imgur.com/a/oae0O](http://imgur.com/a/oae0O)

First image is stock T3D blending, from there it is new blending with blendDepth 0.1,0.2 etc up to 0.9. Last image is blendDepth 0.99

You can set the "blendDepth" on the terrain material like this:

```
new TerrainMaterial()  
{  
   diffuseMap = "art/terrains/Example/sand";  
   diffuseSize = "500";  
   detailMap = "art/terrains/Example/sand_d";  
   detailSize = "2";  
   detailDistance = "50";  
   internalName = "sand2";  
   normalMap = "art/terrains/Example/sand_n";  
   blendDepth = 0.5;  // <---
};
```

You enable the new blending method by setting `$terrain::lerpBlend = false;` (defaults to true). This PR does not contain any UI changes so the new features have to be activated through script. (UI might come in a later PR!)

**Note for the new blending to work properly, the textures HAVE to have a normal map with a heightmap in the alpha channel. If you don't use normal maps, then this texture blending method is not for you.**
